                <note type="updated" update="import" value="fileDesc" import="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml" date-time="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" user="admin"/>
                <note type="updated" update="attribution" import="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml" date-time="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" user="admin">The attribution of this text (Toh. 3843) to Nāgārjuna appears to be in error as it is very clearly a Cittamātra text and is identical in content (though
            a different translation) to Toh. 4058 attributed to Vasubandhu.</note>
                <note type="updated" update="title" import="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml" date-time="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" user="admin">The Sanskrit title provided (Toh. 3843) is a back-translation from the Tibetan, which itself is only marginally intelligible, hence the title provided is taken
            from a translation of the extant Sanskrit manuscript.</note>
                <note type="updated" update="general" import="tengyur-data-3824-3980_PH_new_v2.4.xml" date-time="2021-11-02T14:13:45.147Z" user="admin">The text presents a straight forward exposition with illustrations of the “Three Natures” (trisvabhāva) theory common to the Cittamātra school. Although
            there is a Madhyamaka interpretation of the “Three Natures” (as presented in the “Maitreya” chapters of the Eighteen Thousand Line Perfection of Wisdom Sūtra [chapter 83], and the
            Twenty-Five Thousand Line Perfection of Wisdom Sūtra [chapter 72]), that interpretation is not what is found here.</note>
